Tensions are simmering between warring Free State African National Congress (ANC) factions ahead of two high-profile cases. The Supreme Court of Appeal in Bloemfontein will on Monday preside over the legal challenge regarding the validity of the disputed election of the party leadership in the province. On Friday, former Free State Premier and ANC Secretary-General Ace Magashule, together with seven others and five companies will be appearing in the Bloemfontein Magistrate’s Court. They face, among others, corruption charges relating to the alleged irregular awarding of the more than R220-million asbestos removal tender. Hawks arrest suspects implicated in Free State asbestos project:  Members who are appealing the Free State ANC leadership status have warned Magashule supporters not to support him in court. The group’s spokesperson, Kgomotso Tsitsi, says the ANC should act decisively. Secretary-General Ace Magashule in court: